column30: Looking at the graph, intuition suggests that H is -1. Neonatal and senescent cells are not basally producing CDKN2B (p15 Ink4b) while adult cells are. Since CDKN2B is a inhibitor of the cell cycle, this suggests that adult cells have higher basal resistance to proliferation and growth
Young cells are basally churning out collagen regardless of stimulation. It looks as though senescent and adult cells are also trying to produce collagen but the response is greatly diminished
Differential behaviour with COL4A1/5A1 in senescence than young. While COL1A1/2 are still being produced in senescence, COL4A1/5A1 are actively down regulated with the passage of time
Neonatal and senescent cells produce CTGF, despite senescent being diminished with respect to neonatal. Adult cells however are not producing basal levels of CTGF

DCN plays a role in matrix assembly and binds to type 1 collagen. Absence of DCN being basally produced in senescence suggests a transition of cell purpose from deposition and collagen to something else. Adult cells are still trying to deposit collagen, regardless of being less effective
Elastin. Major component of ECM. Neonatal cells basally churn out ELN while senescence and adult cells do not. This supports the notion of reduced elasticity in dermal tissue with age
Basal production  of ETS1 are dimished with age and senescence
Fibulin. Glycoprotein. Incorporated into fibronectin matrix fibers. Produced with time regardless of age or senescence.

Fibrillin 1. Sub-components of microfibrils which allow skin to stretch. Store TGFb in latent form. Basally produced in both neonatal and adult cells but not in senescence. In line with the idea that neonatal and adult cells are trying to produce ECM while the objective of the senescent cell has changed.
Activates PI3K via FGFR1. Activates angeogenesis. Stored in basement membrane. Adult cells produce less
Fibronectin. Cell adhesion and migration. Production down regulated with time in all cell types – perhaps this is a result of being stationary in vitro and having nowhere to go ?
Glucoronidase beta. Degrades glycosamicoglycans (heparan sulphase). Localized to lysosome. Similar behaviour in basal cells across cell types, though it looks as though adults produce less.
Seems to be produced with time, less so in adults
